{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17619200","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17619200"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:29:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:29:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16543"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16543","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16543"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.04,0.35,0.3,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9234"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75716"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9234","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9234"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16543"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61234"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4904"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"6228"},{"type":"tags","id":"7146"},{"type":"tags","id":"7151"},{"type":"tags","id":"8561"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21882"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21886"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75716","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75716"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents with difficulty maintaining balance while walking. On examination, she demonstrates significant swaying of the trunk and a broad-based, unsteady gait. Brain imaging reveals a focal lesion in her cerebellum.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following cerebellar regions is most likely to be damaged?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lateral hemisphere","Intermediate zone","Vermis","Flocculonodular lobe","Dentate nucleus"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Evermis\u003C/strong\u003E is the midline portion of the cerebellum that primarily controls axial muscles and balance. Damage to this region results in truncal ataxia, characterised by difficulty maintaining upright posture and a broad-based gait.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other regions have different functions:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELateral hemisphere\u003C/strong\u003E controls fine motor movements of distal limbs and is involved in motor planning\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntermediate zone\u003C/strong\u003E coordinates limb movements and regulates muscle tone\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlocculonodular lobe\u003C/strong\u003E maintains balance and coordinates eye movements\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDentate nucleus\u003C/strong\u003E is a deep cerebellar nucleus that relays output from the lateral hemisphere\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe vermis receives input primarily from the vestibular system and spinal cord, allowing it to coordinate trunk and proximal limb movements necessary for maintaining posture and balance.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The cerebellar vermis primarily controls axial muscles and balance, with lesions causing truncal ataxia and impaired balance.","The lateral cerebellum controls fine motor movements of distal limbs, while the intermediate zone coordinates limb movements and muscle tone.","Different regions of the cerebellum have distinct functional roles based on their connections and evolutionary development."],"references":["Sullivan EV. Cognitive functions of the cerebellum. Neuropsychol Rev. 2010 Sep;20(3):227-8. doi: 10.1007/s11065-010-9144-8. Epub 2010 Sep 2. PMID: 20811946; PMCID: PMC4723423","Bare\u0161 M, Hus\u00e1rov\u00e1 I, Lungu OV. Essential tremor, the cerebellum, and motor timing: towards integrating them into one complex entity. Tremor Other Hyperkinet Mov (N Y). 2012;2:tre-02-93-653-1. Epub 2012 Sep 12. PMID: 23439925; PMCID: PMC3572554","Gillig PM, Sanders RD. Psychiatry, neurology, and the role of the cerebellum. Psychiatry (Edgmont). 2010 Sep;7(9):38-43. PMID: 20941351; PMCID: PMC2952646","Hall, J. E., \u0026 Hall, M. E. (2020). Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book: Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61234"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16543"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61234","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61234"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-30T20:19:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-30T20:20:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9234"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75716"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Scien